# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The **Advisory Council on Underwater Archaeology** (ACUA) serves as an international advisory body on issues relating to underwater archaeology, conservation, and submerged cultural resources management.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The ACUA is an independent, non-profit organization closely affiliated with the Society for Historical Archaeology (SHA).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] Its genesis as the Council on Underwater Archaeology was in 1959 and its purpose was fully realized at a meeting in 1963 when a group of archaeologists, historians, and sport divers met in St.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] Paul, Minnesota for the first international Conference on Underwater Archaeology (CUA).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The first joint conference with the then fledgling Society for Historical Archaeology was held in 1970.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] By 1973, the present structure and name of the ACUA were established and shortly thereafter the SHA and CUA conferences merged.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] In 2003, the ACUA and SHA signed a Memorandum of Agreement, formalizing their relationship.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The ACUA awards the competitive George Fischer Student Travel Award annually to provide monetary value in travel support for an international maritime archaeology student to attend and present at the annual Society for Historical and Underwater Archaeology conference.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The aware is named after George Fischer, a founding and emeritus member of the ACUA.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] Since the inaugural award in 2012, students hailing from different countries have benefited from the support to participate in the exchange of ideas at the annual conference.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The ACUA is composed of twelve individuals elected on a rotating basis for four-year terms by the membership of the Society for Historical Archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The members include professionals from state and federal archaeology programs, museums, non-profit institutes, cultural resource management firms, universities, conservation laboratories, and avocational societies involved in underwater archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] The board elects officers for three year terms.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology] All board terms expire at the ACUA business meeting in January.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation ethic is based on the findings of conservation biology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The term conservation biology and its conception as a new field originated with the convening of "The First International Conference on Research in Conservation Biology" held at the University of California, San Diego in La Jolla, California, in 1978 led by American biologists Bruce A.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Soulé with a group of leading university and zoo researchers and conservationists including Kurt Benirschke, Sir Otto Frankel, Thomas Lovejoy, and Jared Diamond.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The meeting was prompted due to concern over tropical deforestation, disappearing species, and eroding genetic diversity within species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The conference and proceedings that resulted sought to initiate the bridging of a gap between theory in ecology and evolutionary genetics on the one hand and conservation policy and practice on the other.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology and the concept of biological diversity (biodiversity) emerged together, helping crystallize the modern era of conservation science and policy.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The inherent multidisciplinary basis for conservation biology has led to new subdisciplines including conservation social science, conservation behavior and conservation physiology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] It stimulated further development of conservation genetics which Otto Frankel had originated first but is now often considered a subdiscipline as well.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The rapid decline of established biological systems around the world means that conservation biology is often referred to as a "Discipline with a deadline".
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is tied closely to ecology in researching the population ecology (dispersal, migration, demographics, effective population size, inbreeding depression, and minimum population viability) of rare or endangered species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is concerned with phenomena that affect the maintenance, loss, and restoration of biodiversity and the science of sustaining evolutionary processes that engender genetic, population, species, and ecosystem diversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The concern stems from estimates suggesting that up to 50% of all species on the planet will disappear within the next 50 years, which will increase poverty and starvation, and will reset the course of evolution on this planet.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Researchers acknowledge that projections are difficult, given the unknown potential impacts of many variables, including species introduction to new biogeographical settings and a non-analog climate.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists research and educate on the trends and process of biodiversity loss, species extinctions, and the negative effect these are having on our capabilities to sustain the well-being of human society.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists work in the field and office, in government, universities, non-profit organizations and industry.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The topics of their research are diverse, because this is an interdisciplinary network with professional alliances in the biological as well as social sciences.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Those dedicated to the cause and profession advocate for a global response to the current biodiversity crisis based on morals, ethics, and scientific reason.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Organizations and citizens are responding to the biodiversity crisis through conservation action plans that direct research, monitoring, and education programs that engage concerns at local through global scales.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There is increasing recognition that conservation is not just about what is achieved but how it is done.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conscious efforts to conserve and protect *global* biodiversity are a recent phenomenon.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Natural resource conservation, however, has a history that extends prior to the age of conservation.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Resource ethics grew out of necessity through direct relations with nature.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Regulation or communal restraint became necessary to prevent selfish motives from taking more than could be locally sustained, therefore compromising the long-term supply for the rest of the community.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This social dilemma with respect to natural resource management is often called the "tragedy of the commons".
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] From this principle, conservation biologists can trace communal resource based ethics throughout cultures as a solution to communal resource conflict.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] For example, the Alaskan Tlingit peoples and the Haida of the Pacific Northwest had resource boundaries, rules, and restrictions among clans with respect to the fishing of sockeye salmon.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] These rules were guided by clan elders who knew lifelong details of each river and stream they managed.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There are numerous examples in history where cultures have followed rules, rituals, and organized practice with respect to communal natural resource management.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The Mauryan emperor Ashoka around 250 BC issued edicts restricting the slaughter of animals and certain kinds of birds, as well as opened veterinary clinics.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation ethics are also found in early religious and philosophical writings.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There are examples in the Tao, Shinto, Hindu, Islamic and Buddhist traditions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Before the 18th century, however, much of European culture considered it a pagan view to admire nature.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Wilderness was denigrated while agricultural development was praised.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] However, as early as AD 680 a wildlife sanctuary was founded on the Farne Islands by St Cuthbert in response to his religious beliefs.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Natural history was a major preoccupation in the 18th century, with grand expeditions and the opening of popular public displays in Europe and North America.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] By 1900 there were 150 natural history museums in Germany, 250 in Great Britain, 250 in the United States, and 300 in France.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationist or conservationist sentiments are a development of the late 18th to early 20th centuries.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Before Charles Darwin set sail on HMS *Beagle*, most people in the world, including Darwin, believed in special creation and that all species were unchanged.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon was one of the first naturalists that questioned this belief.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] He proposed in his 44 volume natural history book that species evolve due to environmental influences.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin was also a naturalist who also suggested that species evolved.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin noted that some species have vestigial structures which are anatomical structures that have no apparent function in the species currently but would have been useful for the species' ancestors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The thinking of these early 18th century naturalists helped to change the mindset and thinking of the early 19th century naturalists.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] By the early 19th century biogeography was ignited through the efforts of Alexander von Humboldt, Charles Lyell and Charles Darwin.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The 19th-century fascination with natural history engendered a fervor to be the first to collect rare specimens with the goal of doing so before they became extinct by other such collectors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Although the work of many 18th and 19th century naturalists were to inspire nature enthusiasts and conservation organizations, their writings, by modern standards, showed insensitivity towards conservation as they would kill hundreds of specimens for their collections.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The modern roots of conservation biology can be found in the late 18th-century Enlightenment period particularly in England and Scotland.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Thinkers including Lord Monboddo described the importance of "preserving nature"; much of this early emphasis had its origins in Christian theology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Scientific conservation principles were first practically applied to the forests of British India.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The Madras Board of Revenue started local conservation efforts in 1842, headed by Alexander Gibson, a professional botanist who systematically adopted a forest conservation program based on scientific principles.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This was the first case of state conservation management of forests in the world.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Governor-General Lord Dalhousie introduced the first permanent and large-scale forest conservation program in the world in 1855, a model that soon spread to other colonies, as well the United States, where Yellowstone National Park was opened in 1872 as the world's first national park.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The term *conservation* came into widespread use in the late 19th century and referred to the management, mainly for economic reasons, of such natural resources as timber, fish, game, topsoil, pastureland, and minerals.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In addition it referred to the preservation of forests (forestry), wildlife (wildlife refuge), parkland, wilderness, and watersheds.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This period also saw the passage of the first conservation legislation and the establishment of the first nature conservation societies.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The Sea Birds Preservation Act 1869 was passed in Britain as the first nature protection law in the world after extensive lobbying from the Association for the Protection of Seabirds and the respected ornithologist Alfred Newton.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Newton was also instrumental in the passage of the first Game laws from 1872, which protected animals during their breeding season so as to prevent the stock from being brought close to extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] One of the first conservation societies was the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, founded in 1889 in Manchester as a protest group campaigning against the use of great crested grebe and kittiwake skins and feathers in fur clothing.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Originally known as "the Plumage League", the group gained popularity and eventually amalgamated with the Fur and Feather League in Croydon, and formed the RSPB.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This meeting led to the formation of the Society for the Promotion of Nature Reserves, which later became the Wildlife Trusts.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In the United States, the Forest Reserve Act of 1891 gave the President power to set aside forest reserves from the land in the public domain.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] John Muir founded the Sierra Club in 1892, and the New York Zoological Society was set up in 1895.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] A series of national forests and preserves were established by Theodore Roosevelt from 1901 to 1909.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The 1916 National Parks Act, included a 'use without impairment' clause, sought by John Muir, which eventually resulted in the removal of a proposal to build a dam in Dinosaur National Monument in 1959.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In the 20th century, Canadian civil servants, including Charles Gordon Hewitt and James Harkin, spearheaded the movement toward wildlife conservation.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In the 21st century professional conservation officers have begun to collaborate with indigenous communities for protecting wildlife in Canada.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Some conservation efforts are yet to fully take hold due to ecological neglect.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] For example in the USA, 21st century bowfishing of native fishes, which amounts to killing wild animals for recreation and disposing of them immediately afterwards, remains unregulated and unmanaged.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In the mid-20th century, efforts arose to target individual species for conservation, notably efforts in big cat conservation in South America led by the New York Zoological Society.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley, Archie Carr and his son Archie Carr III is notable in this era.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley for example, having led expeditions to the Virunga Mountains and observed the mountain gorilla in the wild, became convinced that the species and the area were conservation priorities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] He was instrumental in persuading Albert I of Belgium to act in defense of the mountain gorilla and establish Albert National Park (since renamed Virunga National Park) in what is now Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] By the 1970s, led primarily by work in the United States under the Endangered Species Act along with the Species at Risk Act (SARA) of Canada, Biodiversity Action Plans developed in Australia, Sweden, the United Kingdom, hundreds of species specific protection plans ensued.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Notably the United Nations acted to conserve sites of outstanding cultural or natural importance to the common heritage of mankind.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The programme was adopted by the General Conference of UNESCO in 1972.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] As of 2006, a total of 830 sites are listed: 644 cultural, 162 natural.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Other conservation developments, however, have taken hold throughout the world.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] India, for example, passed the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In 1980, a significant development was the emergence of the urban conservation movement.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] A local organization was established in Birmingham, UK, a development followed in rapid succession in cities across the UK, then overseas.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Although perceived as a grassroots movement, its early development was driven by academic research into urban wildlife.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Initially perceived as radical, the movement's view of conservation being inextricably linked with other human activity has now become mainstream in conservation thought.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Considerable research effort is now directed at urban conservation biology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology originated in 1985.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The late 1990s saw increasing professionalism in the sector, with the maturing of organisations such as the Institute of Ecology and Environmental Management and the Society for the Environment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Since 2000, the concept of landscape scale conservation has risen to prominence, with less emphasis being given to single-species or even single-habitat focused actions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Instead an ecosystem approach is advocated by most mainstream conservationists, although concerns have been expressed by those working to protect some high-profile species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecology has clarified the workings of the biosphere; i.e., the complex interrelationships among humans, other species, and the physical environment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The burgeoning human population and associated agriculture, industry, and the ensuing pollution, have demonstrated how easily ecological relationships can be disrupted.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] becoming extinct during any given time interval.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] It does not represent all marine species, just those that are readily fossilized.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Extinction rates are measured in a variety of ways.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists measure and apply statistical measures of fossil records, rates of habitat loss, and a multitude of other variables such as loss of biodiversity as a function of the rate of habitat loss and site occupancy to obtain such estimates.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] *The Theory of Island Biogeography* is possibly the most significant contribution toward the scientific understanding of both the process and how to measure the rate of species extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The current background extinction rate is estimated to be one species every few years.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Actual extinction rates are estimated to be orders of magnitudes higher.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] While this is important, it's worth noting that there are no models in existence that account for the complexity of unpredictable factors like species movement, a non-analog climate, changing species interactions, evolutionary rates on finer time scales, and many other stochastic variables.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The measure of ongoing species loss is made more complex by the fact that most of the Earth's species have not been described or evaluated.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Estimates vary greatly on how many species actually exist (estimated range: 3,600,000–111,700,000) to how many have received a species binomial (estimated range: 1.5–8 million).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Less than 1 percent of all species that have been described beyond simply noting its existence.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] From these figures, the IUCN reports that 23 percent of vertebrates, 5 percent of invertebrates and 70 percent of plants that have been evaluated are designated as endangered or threatened.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Better knowledge is being constructed by The Plant List for actual numbers of species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic conservation planning is an effective way to seek and identify efficient and effective types of reserve design to capture or sustain the highest priority biodiversity values and to work with communities in support of local ecosystems.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists regularly prepare detailed conservation plans for grant proposals or to effectively coordinate their plan of action and to identify best management practices (e.g.).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic strategies generally employ the services of Geographic Information Systems to assist in the decision-making process.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The SLOSS debate is often considered in planning.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology was defined by Steven J.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology is particularly relevant to practitioners in that it has the potential to generate cause-and-effect relationships and reveal the factors that contribute to population declines.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology is a global community of conservation professionals dedicated to advancing the science and practice of conserving biodiversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology as a discipline reaches beyond biology, into subjects such as philosophy, law, economics, humanities, arts, anthropology, and education.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Within biology, conservation genetics and evolution are immense fields unto themselves, but these disciplines are of prime importance to the practice and profession of conservation biology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservationists introduce bias when they support policies using qualitative description, such as habitat *degradation*, or *healthy* ecosystems.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists advocate for reasoned and sensible management of natural resources and do so with a disclosed combination of science, reason, logic, and values in their conservation management plans.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This sort of advocacy is similar to the medical profession advocating for healthy lifestyle options, both are beneficial to human well-being yet remain scientific in their approach.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There is a movement in conservation biology suggesting a new form of leadership is needed to mobilize conservation biology into a more effective discipline that is able to communicate the full scope of the problem to society at large.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The movement proposes an adaptive leadership approach that parallels an adaptive management approach.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The concept is based on a new philosophy or leadership theory steering away from historical notions of power, authority, and dominance.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership is reflective and more equitable as it applies to any member of society who can mobilize others toward meaningful change using communication techniques that are inspiring, purposeful, and collegial.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership and mentoring programs are being implemented by conservation biologists through organizations such as the Aldo Leopold Leadership Program.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation may be classified as either in-situ conservation, which is protecting an endangered species in its natural habitat, or ex-situ conservation, which occurs outside the natural habitat.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In-situ conservation involves protecting or restoring the habitat.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Ex-situ conservation, on the other hand, involves protection outside of an organism's natural habitat, such as on reservations or in gene banks, in circumstances where viable populations may not be present in the natural habitat.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation of habitats like forest, water or soil in its natural state is crucial for any species depending in it to thrive.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Making a new environment which looks alike the original is less effective than preserving original habitats.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] An approach in Nepal named reforestation campaign has helped increase the density and area covered by the original forests which proved to be better than creating entirely new environment after original one is let to lost.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Old Forests Store More Carbon than Young Ones as proved by latest researches, so it is more crucial to protect the old ones.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The reforestation campaign launched by Himalayan Adventure Therapy in Nepal basically visits the old forests in periodic basis which are vulnerable to loss of density and the area covered due to unplanned urbanization activities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Then they plant the new saplings of same tree families of that existing forest in the areas where the old forest has been lost and also plant those saplings to the barren areas connected to the forest.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This maintains the density and area covered by the forest.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Also, non-interference may be used, which is termed a preservationist method.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationists advocate for giving areas of nature and species a protected existence that halts interference from the humans.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In this regard, conservationists differ from preservationists in the social dimension, as conservation biology engages society and seeks equitable solutions for both society and ecosystems.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Some preservationists emphasize the potential of biodiversity in a world without humans.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring is the systematic collection of data relevant to the ecology of a species or habitat at repeating intervals with defined methods.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring for environmental and ecological metrics is an important part of any successful conservation initiative.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Unfortunately, long-term data for many species and habitats is not available in many cases.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] A lack of historical data on species populations, habitats, and ecosystems means that any current or future conservation work will have to make assumptions to determine if the work is having any effect on the population or ecosystem health.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring can provide early warning signals of deleterious effects (from human activities or natural changes in an environment) on an ecosystem and its species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] In order for signs of negative trends in ecosystem or species health to be detected, monitoring methods must be carried out at appropriate time intervals, and the metric must be able to capture the trend of the population or habitat as a whole.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring can include the continued measuring of many biological, ecological, and environmental metrics including annual breeding success, population size estimates, water quality, biodiversity (which can be measured in many way, i.e.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] When determining which metrics to monitor for a conservation project, it is important to understand how an ecosystem functions and what role different species and abiotic factors have within the system.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Another benefit of ecological monitoring is the hard evidence it provides scientists to use for advising policy makers and funding bodies about conservation efforts.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Not only is ecological monitoring data important for convincing politicians, funders, and the public why a conservation program is important to implement, but also to keep them convinced that a program should be continued to be supported.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There is plenty of debate on how conservation resources can be used most efficiently; even within ecological monitoring, there is debate on which metrics that money, time and personnel should be dedicated to for the best chance of making a positive impact.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The concept of bioindicators / indicator species can be applied to ecological monitoring as a way to investigate how pollution is affecting an ecosystem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Species like amphibians and birds are highly susceptible to pollutants in their environment due to their behaviours and physiological features that cause them to absorb pollutants at a faster rate than other species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Amphibians spend parts of their time in the water and on land, making them susceptible to changes in both environments.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] They also have very permeable skin that allows them to breathe and intake water, which means they also take any air or water-soluble pollutants in as well.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Birds often cover a wide range in habitat types annually, and also generally revisit the same nesting site each year.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This makes it easier for researchers to track ecological effects at both an individual and a population level for the species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Many conservation researchers believe that having a long-term ecological monitoring program should be a priority for conservation projects, protected areas, and regions where environmental harm mitigation is used.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists are interdisciplinary researchers that practice ethics in the biological and social sciences.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Chan states that conservationists must advocate for biodiversity and can do so in a scientifically ethical manner by not promoting simultaneous advocacy against other competing values.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Aldo Leopold was a classical thinker and writer on such conservation ethics whose philosophy, ethics and writings are still valued and revisited by modern conservation biologists.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) has organized a global assortment of scientists and research stations across the planet to monitor the changing state of nature in an effort to tackle the extinction crisis.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN provides annual updates on the status of species conservation through its Red List.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN Red List serves as an international conservation tool to identify those species most in need of conservation attention and by providing a global index on the status of biodiversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] More than the dramatic rates of species loss, however, conservation scientists note that the sixth mass extinction is a biodiversity crisis requiring far more action than a priority focus on rare, endemic or endangered species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Concerns for biodiversity loss covers a broader conservation mandate that looks at ecological processes, such as migration, and a holistic examination of biodiversity at levels beyond the species, including genetic, population and ecosystem diversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Extensive, systematic, and rapid rates of biodiversity loss threatens the sustained well-being of humanity by limiting supply of ecosystem services that are otherwise regenerated by the complex and evolving holistic network of genetic and ecosystem diversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] While the conservation status of species is employed extensively in conservation management, some scientists highlight that it is the common species that are the primary source of exploitation and habitat alteration by humanity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, common species are often undervalued despite their role as the primary source of ecosystem services.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] While most in the community of conservation science "stress the importance" of sustaining biodiversity, there is debate on how to prioritize genes, species, or ecosystems, which are all components of biodiversity (e.g.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The costs of discovering, naming, and mapping out the distribution of every species, they argue, is an ill-advised conservation venture.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] They reason it is better to understand the significance of the ecological roles of species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Biodiversity hotspots and coldspots are a way of recognizing that the spatial concentration of genes, species, and ecosystems is not uniformly distributed on the Earth's surface.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Those arguing in favor of setting priorities for coldspots point out that there are other measures to consider beyond biodiversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] They point out that emphasizing hotspots downplays the importance of the social and ecological connections to vast areas of the Earth's ecosystems where biomass, not biodiversity, reigns supreme.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] It is estimated that 36 percent of the Earth's surface, encompassing 38.9 percent of the worlds vertebrates, lacks the endemic species to qualify as biodiversity hotspot.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, measures show that maximizing protections for biodiversity does not capture ecosystem services any better than targeting randomly chosen regions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Population level biodiversity (mostly in coldspots) are disappearing at a rate that is ten times that at the species level.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The level of importance in addressing biomass versus endemism as a concern for conservation biology is highlighted in literature measuring the level of threat to global ecosystem carbon stocks that do not necessarily reside in areas of endemism.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] A hotspot priority approach would not invest so heavily in places such as steppes, the Serengeti, the Arctic, or taiga.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] These areas contribute a great abundance of population (not species) level biodiversity and ecosystem services, including cultural value and planetary nutrient cycling.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Those in favor of the hotspot approach point out that species are irreplaceable components of the global ecosystem, they are concentrated in places that are most threatened, and should therefore receive maximal strategic protections.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This is a hotspot approach because the priority is set to target species level concerns over population level or biomass.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Species richness and genetic biodiversity contributes to and engenders ecosystem stability, ecosystem processes, evolutionary adaptability, and biomass.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Both sides agree, however, that conserving biodiversity is necessary to reduce the extinction rate and identify an inherent value in nature; the debate hinges on how to prioritize limited conservation resources in the most cost-effective way.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists have started to collaborate with leading global economists to determine how to measure the wealth and services of nature and to make these values apparent in global market transactions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This system of accounting is called *natural capital* and would, for example, register the value of an ecosystem before it is cleared to make way for development.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The WWF publishes its *Living Planet Report* and provides a global index of biodiversity by monitoring approximately 5,000 populations in 1,686 species of vertebrate (mammals, birds, fish, reptiles, and amphibians) and report on the trends in much the same way that the stock market is tracked.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This method of measuring the global economic benefit of nature has been endorsed by the G8+5 leaders and the European Commission.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Nature sustains many ecosystem services that benefit humanity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Many of the Earth's ecosystem services are public goods without a market and therefore no price or value.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] When the *stock market* registers a financial crisis, traders on Wall Street are not in the business of trading stocks for much of the planet's living natural capital stored in ecosystems.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There is no natural stock market with investment portfolios into sea horses, amphibians, insects, and other creatures that provide a sustainable supply of ecosystem services that are valuable to society.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The ecological footprint of society has exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity limits of the planet's ecosystems by about 30 percent, which is the same percentage of vertebrate populations that have registered decline from 1970 through 2005.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] There is a relationship, a correlation, between markets and natural capital, and social income inequity and biodiversity loss.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This means that there are greater rates of biodiversity loss in places where the inequity of wealth is greatest, an example of this would be the Perdido Key beach mouse.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This is an endangered species that its demis started because of continued development along beaches, these mice leave in sand dunes and play an important role within this ecosystem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] These mice help the grass grow inside the sandunes, they eat this grass and then this leads to then spreading seeds throughout the beach creating more grass.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Sand dunes may not seem that important but they do act as a barrier for any sort of storm coming from the ocean such as hurricanes.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Although a direct market comparison of natural capital is likely insufficient in terms of human value, one measure of ecosystem services suggests the contribution amounts to trillions of dollars yearly.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] For example, one segment of North American forests has been assigned an annual value of 250 billion dollars; as another example, honey bee pollination is estimated to provide between 10 and 18 billion dollars of value yearly.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The value of ecosystem services on one New Zealand island has been imputed to be as great as the GDP of that region.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] This planetary wealth is being lost at an incredible rate as the demands of human society is exceeding the bio-regenerative capacity of the Earth.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] While biodiversity and ecosystems are resilient, the danger of losing them is that humans cannot recreate many ecosystem functions through technological innovation.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Some species, called a *keystone species* form a central supporting hub unique to their ecosystem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The loss of such a species results in a collapse in ecosystem function, as well as the loss of coexisting species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Keystone species are usually predators due to their ability to control the population of prey in their ecosystem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The importance of a keystone species was shown by the extinction of the Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) through its interaction with sea otters, sea urchins, and kelp.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Kelp beds grow and form nurseries in shallow waters to shelter creatures that support the food chain.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Sea urchins feed on kelp, while sea otters feed on sea urchins.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] With the rapid decline of sea otters due to overhunting, sea urchin populations grazed unrestricted on the kelp beds and the ecosystem collapsed.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Left unchecked, the urchins destroyed the shallow water kelp communities that supported the Steller's sea cow's diet and hastened their demise.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The sea otter was thought to be a keystone species because the coexistence of many ecological associates in the kelp beds relied upon otters for their survival.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] However this was later questioned by Turvey and Risley, who showed that hunting alone would have driven the Steller's sea cow extinct.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] An *indicator species* has a narrow set of ecological requirements, therefore they become useful targets for observing the health of an ecosystem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Some animals, such as amphibians with their semi-permeable skin and linkages to wetlands, have an acute sensitivity to environmental harm and thus may serve as a *miner's canary*.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Indicator species are monitored in an effort to capture environmental degradation through pollution or some other link to proximate human activities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Government regulators, consultants, or NGOs regularly monitor indicator species, however, there are limitations coupled with many practical considerations that must be followed for the approach to be effective.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] It is generally recommended that multiple indicators (genes, populations, species, communities, and landscape) be monitored for effective conservation measurement that prevents harm to the complex, and often unpredictable, response from ecosystem dynamics (Noss, 1997).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] An example of an *umbrella species* is the monarch butterfly, because of its lengthy migrations and aesthetic value.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] The monarch migrates across North America, covering multiple ecosystems and so requires a large area to exist.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Any protections afforded to the monarch butterfly will at the same time umbrella many other species and habitats.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] An umbrella species is often used as *flagship species*, which are species, such as the giant panda, the blue whale, the tiger, the mountain gorilla and the monarch butterfly, that capture the public's attention and attract support for conservation measures.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p01] Paradoxically, however, conservation bias towards flagship species sometimes threatens other species of chief concern.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists study trends and process from the paleontological past to the ecological present as they gain an understanding of the context related to species extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] It is generally accepted that there have been five major global mass extinctions that register in Earth's history.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] These include: the Ordovician (440 mya), Devonian (370 mya), Permian–Triassic (252 mya), Triassic–Jurassic (201 mya), and Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event (66 mya) extinction spasms.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The latest *Living Planet Report* by the World Wide Fund for Nature estimates that we have exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity of the planet, requiring 1.6 Earths to support the demands placed on our natural resources.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists are dealing with and have published evidence from all corners of the planet indicating that humanity may be causing the sixth and fastest planetary extinction event.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] It has been suggested that an unprecedented number of species is becoming extinct in what is known as the Holocene extinction event.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The global extinction rate may be approximately 1,000 times higher than the natural background extinction rate.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] It is estimated that two-thirds of all mammal genera and one-half of all mammal species weighing at least 44 kilograms (97 lb) have gone extinct in the last 50,000 years.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The Global Amphibian Assessment reports that amphibians are declining on a global scale faster than any other vertebrate group, with over 32 percent of all surviving species being threatened with extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The surviving populations are in continual decline in 43 percent of those that are threatened.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Since the mid-1980s the actual rates of extinction have exceeded 211 times rates measured from the fossil record.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] However, "The current amphibian extinction rate may range from 25,039 to 45,474 times the background extinction rate for amphibians." The global extinction trend occurs in every major vertebrate group that is being monitored.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] For example, 23 percent of all mammals and 12 percent of all birds are Red Listed by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), meaning they too are threatened with extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Even though extinction is natural, the decline in species is happening at such an incredible rate that evolution can simply not match, therefore, leading to the greatest continual mass extinction on Earth.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Humans have dominated the planet and our high consumption of resources, along with the pollution generated is affecting the environments in which other species live.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] There are a wide variety of species that humans are working to protect such as the Hawaiian Crow and the Whooping Crane of Texas.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] People can also take action on preserving species by advocating and voting for global and national policies that improve climate, under the concepts of climate mitigation and climate restoration.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The Earth's oceans demand particular attention as climate change continues to alter pH levels, making it uninhabitable for organisms with shells which dissolve as a result.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Global assessments of coral reefs of the world continue to report drastic and rapid rates of decline.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] By 2000, 27 percent of the world's coral reef ecosystems had effectively collapsed.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The largest period of decline occurred in a dramatic "bleaching" event in 1998, where approximately 16 percent of all the coral reefs in the world disappeared in less than a year.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] *Coral bleaching* is caused by a mixture of environmental stresses, including increases in ocean temperatures and acidity, causing both the release of symbiotic algae and death of corals.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Decline and extinction risk in coral reef biodiversity has risen dramatically in the past ten years.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The loss of coral reefs, which are predicted to go extinct in the next century, threatens the balance of global biodiversity, will have huge economic impacts, and endangers food security for hundreds of millions of people.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biology plays an important role in international agreements covering the world's oceans and other issues pertaining to biodiversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The oceans are threatened by acidification due to an increase in CO2 levels.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] This is a most serious threat to societies relying heavily upon oceanic natural resources.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] A concern is that the majority of all marine species will not be able to evolve or acclimate in response to the changes in the ocean chemistry.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The prospects of averting mass extinction seems unlikely when "90% of all of the large (average approximately ≥50 kg), open ocean tuna, billfishes, and sharks in the ocean" are reportedly gone.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Given the scientific review of current trends, the ocean is predicted to have few surviving multi-cellular organisms with only microbes left to dominate marine ecosystems.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Serious concerns also being raised about taxonomic groups that do not receive the same degree of social attention or attract funds as the vertebrates.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] These include fungal (including lichen-forming species), invertebrate (particularly insect) and plant communities where the vast majority of biodiversity is represented.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation of fungi and conservation of insects, in particular, are both of pivotal importance for conservation biology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] As mycorrhizal symbionts, and as decomposers and recyclers, fungi are essential for sustainability of forests.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The value of insects in the biosphere is enormous because they outnumber all other living groups in measure of species richness.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The greatest bulk of biomass on land is found in plants, which is sustained by insect relations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] This great ecological value of insects is countered by a society that often reacts negatively toward these aesthetically 'unpleasant' creatures.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] One area of concern in the insect world that has caught the public eye is the mysterious case of missing honey bees (*Apis mellifera*).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Honey bees provide an indispensable ecological services through their acts of pollination supporting a huge variety of agriculture crops.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The use of honey and wax have become vastly used throughout the world.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The sudden disappearance of bees leaving empty hives or colony collapse disorder (CCD) is not uncommon.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] However, in 16-month period from 2006 through 2007, 29 percent of 577 beekeepers across the United States reported CCD losses in up to 76 percent of their colonies.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] This sudden demographic loss in bee numbers is placing a strain on the agricultural sector.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The cause behind the massive declines is puzzling scientists.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Pests, pesticides, and global warming are all being considered as possible causes.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Another highlight that links conservation biology to insects, forests, and climate change is the mountain pine beetle (*Dendroctonus ponderosae*) epidemic of British Columbia, Canada, which has infested 470,000 km2 (180,000 sq mi) of forested land since 1999.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] An action plan has been prepared by the Government of British Columbia to address this problem.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] A large proportion of parasite species are threatened by extinction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] A few of them are being eradicated as pests of humans or domestic animals; however, most of them are harmless.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites also make up a significant amount of global biodiversity, given that they make up a large proportion of all species on earth, making them of increasingly prevalent conservation interest.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Threats include the decline or fragmentation of host populations, or the extinction of host species.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites are intricately woven into ecosystems and food webs, thereby occupying valuable roles in ecosystem structure and function.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Today, many threats to biodiversity exist.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] An acronym that can be used to express the top threats of present-day H.I.P.P.O stands for Habitat Loss, Invasive Species, Pollution, Human Population, and Overharvesting.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The primary threats to biodiversity are habitat destruction (such as deforestation, agricultural expansion, urban development), and overexploitation (such as wildlife trade).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Habitat fragmentation also poses challenges, because the global network of protected areas only covers 11.5 percent of the Earth's surface.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] A significant consequence of fragmentation and lack of linked protected areas is the reduction of animal migration on a global scale.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Considering that billions of tonnes of biomass are responsible for nutrient cycling across the Earth, the reduction of migration is a serious matter for conservation biology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] However, human activities need not necessarily cause irreparable harm to the biosphere.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] With conservation management and planning for biodiversity at all levels, from genes to ecosystems, there are examples where humans mutually coexist in a sustainable way with nature.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Even with the current threats to biodiversity there are ways we can improve the current condition and start anew.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Many of the threats to biodiversity, including disease and climate change, are reaching inside borders of protected areas, leaving them 'not-so protected' (e.g.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Climate change, for example, is often cited as a serious threat in this regard, because there is a feedback loop between species extinction and the release of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Ecosystems store and cycle large amounts of carbon which regulates global conditions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] In present day, there have been major climate shifts with temperature changes making survival of some species difficult.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The effects of global warming add a catastrophic threat toward a mass extinction of global biological diversity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Numerous more species are predicted to face unprecedented levels of extinction risk due to population increase, climate change and economic development in the future.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservationists have claimed that not all the species can be saved, and they have to decide which their efforts should be used to protect.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] This concept is known as the Conservation Triage.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The extinction threat is estimated to range from 15 to 37 percent of all species by 2050, or 50 percent of all species over the next 50 years.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/conservation-biology-p02] The current extinction rate is 100–100,000 times more rapid today than the last several billion years.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer was a true pioneer in the field of underwater archaeology and his students are now professors in the U.S. and abroad, serve as state, federal, and territorial archaeologists, direct non-profit research organizations, and work in the private sector.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer taught, as a volunteer at no cost to the university, for almost 30 years at Florida State University, which enabled their underwater archaeology program and introduced hundreds of students to this field.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer was born in Susanville, Lassen County, to George August Fischer, a forester with the United States Forest Service, and Ruth Robertson Fischer, a school teacher.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He was raised in various small towns in northern California, including Alturus, Quincy and Tulelake.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] While in Tulelake, his mother taught school children at the Tule Lake War Relocation Center, and found it more convenient to bring young George along and teach him with the interned Japanese children.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer soon distinguished himself as the only Caucasian child that was hurling stones at the guards during recess.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He met his wife, Nancy (Jane) George Fischer while attending Stanford and they were married on June 20, 1961.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] They had a son while Fischer was stationed at Montezuma Castle National Monument in Arizona.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] They lived in Tallahassee, Florida during his career with the Southeast Archeological Center and Florida State University and after his retirement.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He died in Tallahassee, Florida, on May 29, 2016.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer attended Stanford University, performing his Undergraduate work from 1955 to 1960 and earning his Bachelor of Arts in Anthropology, with minor concentrations in English and Geology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He continued with graduate school at Stanford from 1960–62 and has completed all requirements for his Master of Arts in Anthropology except thesis.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer dabbled part-time as a special student at Florida State University from 1972 to 1973 while employed at the Southeast Archaeological Center.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] George Fischer was employed with the National Park Service from 1959 to 1988, starting as a seasonal Park Ranger and archaeologist from 1959 to 1962 in Mesa Verde National Park and Wupatki National Monument.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In 1962 he became a full-time employee with the NPS as Park Archaeologist at Montezuma Castle National Monument, and in 1964 he took a position as the Park Archaeologist at Ocmulgee National Monument.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In 1966 Fischer moved on to become a Staff Archaeologist at the Division of Archaeology and Anthropology for the NPS in Washington, D.C.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] There Fischer performed general archaeological resource management and research and was able to pursue interests in underwater archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] 1972 saw Fischer transferring to Tallahassee to take a position as a Research Archaeologist at the Southeast Archaeological Center, and that institution's close association with the Florida State University Department of Anthropology led to Fischer's work with archaeology faculty and students there.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Upon his retirement from the NPS in 1988, Fischer became a Courtesy Assistant Professor for the Department of Anthropology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer's instruction and mentoring capacities lessened in the late 1990s as he shifted more into retirement mode.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Projects in Florida outside the National Park System included investigations at Fort Picolata, St.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] John's County; a survey for HMS *Fox* (1799) at St.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He also taught portions of workshops that the Academic Diving Program has sponsored for outside agencies.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In the earliest underwater archaeological investigations by the Park Service (October, 1968), Fischer directed a survey and testing of Montezuma Well, Montezuma Castle National Monument, Arizona.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] From July to September, 1969, Fischer served as field coordinator on the excavation of the 19th century steamboat *Bertrand* at Desoto National Wildlife Refuge on the Missouri River near Blair, Nebraska.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Over 200,000 items were excavated from the wreck, whole objects in incredible condition, still packed in the original crates, with the names of the manufacturers, shippers and consignees; all dated to the morning of April 1, 1865.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] This opened his eyes to the "time capsule" nature of historic shipwreck sites, allowing one to see a specific day and an event caught in time, rather than working with fragments of artifacts and historical trash.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In 1970 George Fischer headed up what came to be one of the first serious underwater archaeology investigations by National Park Service starting with a terrestrial metal detector survey and preliminary assessment of underwater archaeological resources at Padre Island National Seashore in Texas.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Preliminary research led to an underwater archaeological survey of 1554 Spanish Plate Fleet wrecks there, and excavation of the Galleon *San Esteban*, sponsored by Texas Antiquities Committee.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fort Jefferson is a US Third System Fort 70 miles west of Key West in the Gulf of Mexico, and is the largest brick masonry fortification in the western hemisphere.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In the late 1960s and early 1970s Fischer led evaluations of underwater archaeological resources, limited underwater archaeological survey and excavations, and extensive underwater archaeological survey and testing activities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] The 1969 work marked the first extensive shipwreck survey by the NPS on park property, noting more than 20 sites.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] He also participated with staff of Earth Satellite Corporation in a remote sensing survey for historic shipwreck sites, and assisted in analysis of data.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Work was conducted at Fort Jefferson in 1981 and 1982 in partnership with Florida State University.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] In the summer of 1981 and 1982 Fischer directed underwater archaeological investigations of what is considered the wreck of the *Nuestra Señora del Rosario* of the 1622 Spanish fleet, as well as an unidentified patache of the same fleet.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] This investigation revealed what could represent one of the pataches that was sent to salvage the *Rosario* less than a month after the hurricane that sank it, possibly documenting the speed with which the Spanish salvaged their own wrecks.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] HMS *Fowey* was a fifth rate British warship, carrying 44 guns and over 200 men, captained by a descendant of Sir Francis Drake's brother.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] It had scored victories over French and Spanish ships in battle, but was lost on a reef at what is now known as the Legare Anchorage in Biscayne National Park in 1748.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] The sunken vessel became the subject of an ownership dispute with a part-time treasure salvor who presumed that it was part of the Spanish treasure fleet.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] This activity is seen by many of his colleagues and former students as George Fischer's defining act.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer was also a founding member of the Advisory Council on Underwater Archaeology, an international committee of the Society for Historical Archaeology that provides advice and assistance to governments, institutions, and individuals on matters relating to the field.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] During the period of Fischer's tenure as a courtesy professor the FSU Coastal and Marine Laboratory's Academic Diving Program, established in 1975, grew to one of the largest and most active diving research, support, and training programs in the United States.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] The Marine Lab and Academic Diving Program traditionally supports the research diving needs of faculty and students from many departments, as well as several outside agencies, including the Florida Geological Survey and the US Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] Fischer assisted or co-instructed courses in scientific diving techniques and project management through the Florida State University Academic Diving Program from 1976 through his retirement from the Park Service in 1988, and continued as a co-instructor until 2002.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/george-r-fischer] His input and continuity over three decades was instrumental in the expansion and ongoing development of this program.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] The **International Advisory Council** (**IAC**) rules the International Teletraffic Congress (ITC).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] ITC was created in 1955 by Arne Jensen to initially cater to the emerging need to understand and model traffic in telephone networks using stochastic methodologies, and to bring together researchers with these considerations as a common theme.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] The IAC gathers a number of technical experts, from universities and the research arms of key corporations in the industry, from countries having a strong tradition in teletraffic development.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] ITC congresses were organized on most continents.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] That time ITU was the leading standardization in telecommunications.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/international-advisory-council] The long tradition of ITC in connection with ITU fostered the liaison activity in standardization and in the development program.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] A **memorandum of understanding** (**MoU**) is a type of agreement between two (bilateral) or more (multilateral) parties.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] It expresses a convergence of will between the parties, indicating an intended common line of action.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] It is often used either in cases where parties do not imply a legal commitment or in situations where the parties cannot create a legally enforceable agreement.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] It is a more formal alternative to a gentlemen's agreement.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] Whether a document constitutes a binding contract depends only on the presence or absence of well-defined legal elements in the text proper of the document (the so-called "four corners").
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] The required elements are offer and acceptance, consideration, and the intention to be legally bound (*animus contrahendi*).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] In the US, the specifics can differ slightly depending on whether the contract is for goods (so falling under the Uniform Commercial Code) or services (falling under the common law of the state).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] Many companies and government agencies use MoUs to define a relationship between departments, agencies or closely held companies.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] In the United Kingdom and other commonwealth countries, such as New Zealand, the term MoU is commonly used to refer to an agreement between parts of The Crown.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] The term is often used in the context of devolution, for example the 1999 concordat between the central Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and the Scottish Environment Directorate.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] MoUs can also be used between a government agency and a non-commercial, non-governmental organization.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] In international relations, MoUs fall under the broad category of treaties and should be registered in the United Nations treaty collection.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] In practice and in spite of the United Nations Office of Legal Affairs' insistence that registration be done to avoid 'secret diplomacy', MoUs are sometimes kept confidential.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] As a matter of law, the title of MoU does not necessarily mean the document is binding or not binding under international law.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] To determine whether a particular MoU is meant to be a legally binding document (i.e., a treaty), one needs to examine the parties' intent as well as the signatories' position (e.g., Minister of Foreign Affairs vs.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] A careful analysis of the wording will also clarify the exact nature of the document.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] The International Court of Justice has provided some insight into the determination of the legal status of a document in the landmark case of *Qatar v.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] One advantage of MoUs over more formal instruments is that, because obligations under international law may be avoided, they can often be put into effect without requiring legislative approval.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] Hence, MoUs are often used to modify and adapt existing treaties, in which case these MoUs have factual treaty status.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] The decision concerning ratification, however, is determined by the parties' internal law and depends to a large degree on the subject agreed upon.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] MoUs that are kept confidential (i.e., not registered with the UN) cannot be enforced before any UN organ, and it may be concluded that no obligations under international law have been created.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/memorandum-of-understanding] Although MoUs in the multilateral field are seldom seen, the transnational aviation agreements are actually MoUs.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are subject to a non-distribution constraint, meaning that any revenue exceeding expenses must be used to further the organization’s purpose.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Depending on local laws, nonprofits may include charities, political organizations, schools, hospitals, business associations, churches, foundations, social clubs, and cooperatives.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In some countries nonprofit entities can obtain tax-exempt status and may also qualify to receive tax-deductible contributions; however, an organization can still be a nonprofit without having tax exemption.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Key aspects of nonprofit organizations are their ability to fulfill their mission with respect to accountability, integrity, trustworthiness, honesty, and openness to every person who has invested time, money, and faith into the organization.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are accountable to the donors, founders, volunteers, program recipients, and the public community.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Theoretically, for a nonprofit that seeks to finance its operations through donations, public confidence is a factor in the amount of money that a nonprofit organization is able to raise.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Presumably, the more a nonprofit focuses on their mission, the more public confidence they will gain.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] This may result in more money for the organization.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are not driven by generating profit, but they must bring in enough income to pursue their social goals.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits are able to raise money in different ways.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] This includes income from donations from individual donors or foundations, sponsorship from corporations, government funding, programs, services, merchandise sales, and investments.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] With an increase in NPOs since 2010, some organizations have adopted competitive advantages to create revenue for themselves to remain financially stable.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Donations from private individuals or organizations can change each year and government grants have diminished.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] With changes in funding from year to year, many nonprofit organizations have been moving toward increasing the diversity of their funding sources.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] For example, many nonprofits that have relied on government grants have started fundraising efforts to appeal to individual donors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Most nonprofits have staff that work for the organization, possibly using volunteers to perform the nonprofit's services under the direction of the paid staff.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits must be careful to balance the salaries paid to staff against the money paid to provide services to the nonprofit's beneficiaries.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Organizations whose salary expenses are too high relative to their program expenses may face regulatory scrutiny.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some have the misconception that nonprofit organizations may not make a profit.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Although the goal of nonprofits is not specifically to maximize profits, they still have to operate as a fiscally responsible business.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] They must manage their income (grants, donations, and income from services) and expenses so as to remain a fiscally viable entity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits have the responsibility of focusing on being professional and financially responsible, replacing self-interest and profit motive with mission motive.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Though nonprofits are managed differently from for-profit businesses, they have felt pressure to be more businesslike.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] To combat private and public business growth in the public service industry, some nonprofits have modeled their business management and mission, shifting their reason of existing to establish sustainability and growth.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Setting effective missions is a key for the successful management of nonprofit organizations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] There are three important conditions for effective mission: opportunity, competence, and commitment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] One way of managing the sustainability of nonprofit organizations is to establish strong relations with donor groups.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] This requires a donor marketing strategy, something many nonprofits lack.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations need to motivate staff, maintain and communicate a vision, set a strategic direction, manage change effectively, and provide a safe working environment for employees, volunteers, and visitors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] These issues are comparable to those affecting a commercial business but factors which place a nonprofit organization at risk have been identified such as lack of direction or clear purpose, over-centralized management and decision-making, and lack of engagement with staff.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some nonprofit organizations provide public goods that are undersupplied by government.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] NPOs have a wide diversity of structures and purposes.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some of the above must be (in most jurisdictions in the US at least) expressed in the organization's charter of establishment or constitution.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Others may be provided by the supervising authority at each particular jurisdiction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] While affiliations will not affect a legal status, they may be taken into consideration by legal proceedings as an indication of purpose.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Most countries have laws that regulate the establishment and management of NPOs and that require compliance with corporate governance regimes.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Most larger organizations are required to publish their financial reports detailing their income and expenditure publicly.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In many aspects, they are similar to corporate business entities though there are often significant differences.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Both non-profit and for-profit corporate entities must have board members or trustees who owe the organization a fiduciary duty of loyalty and trust.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A notable exception to this involves churches, which are often not required to disclose finances to anyone, including church members.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, nonprofit organizations are formed by filing bylaws, articles of incorporation, or both in the state in which they expect to operate.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The act of incorporation creates a legal entity enabling the organization to be treated as a distinct body (corporation) by law and to enter into business dealings, form contracts, and own property as individuals or for-profit corporations can.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] There is an important distinction in the US between *non-profit* and *not-for-profit organizations* (NFPOs); while an NFPO does not profit its owners, and money goes into running the organization, it is not required to operate for the public good.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] An example is a sports club, whose purpose is its members' enjoyment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The names used and precise regulations vary from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits can have members, but many do not.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The nonprofit may also be a trust or association of members.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The organization may be controlled by its members who elect the board of directors, board of governors, or board of trustees.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A nonprofit may have a delegate structure to allow for the representation of groups or corporations as members.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Alternatively, it may be a non-membership organization and the board of directors may elect its own successors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The two major types of nonprofit organizations are membership and board-only.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A membership organization elects the board and has regular meetings and the power to amend the bylaws.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A board-only organization typically has a self-selected board and a membership whose powers are limited to those delegated to it by the board.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A board-only organization's bylaws may even state that the organization does not have any membership, although the organization's literature may refer to its donors or service recipients as 'members'.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Examples of such organizations are FairVote and the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The Model Nonprofit Corporation Act imposes many complexities and requirements on membership decision-making.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Accordingly, many organizations, such as the Wikimedia Foundation, have formed board-only structures.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The National Association of Parliamentarians has generated concerns about the implications of this trend for the future of openness, accountability, and understanding of public concerns in nonprofit organizations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A rebuttal to this might be that as nonprofit organizations grow and seek larger donations, the degree of scrutiny increases, including expectations of audited financial statements.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A further rebuttal might be that NPOs are constrained, by their choice of legal structure, from financial benefit as far as distribution of profit to members and directors is concerned.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] According to the National Center for Charitable Statistics (NCCS), there are more than 1.5 million nonprofit organizations registered in the United States, including public charities, private foundations, and other nonprofit organizations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] According to the Giving USA 2025 report, which details philanthropic data from 2024, charitable giving in the United States reached an estimated $557.08 billion.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In addition to financial support, volunteering remains a cornerstone of the sector.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A 2025 report from AmeriCorps found that 56.7 million adults formally volunteered with an organization, contributing an estimated $145 billion in economic value to their communities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, both nonprofit organizations and *not-for-profit organizations* may be tax-exempt.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] There are various types of nonprofit exemptions, such as 501(c)(3) organizations that are a religious, charitable, or educational-based organization that does not influence state and federal legislation, and 501(c)(7) organizations that are for pleasure, recreation, or another nonprofit purpose.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] There is an important distinction in the US between *non-profit* and *not-for-profit organizations* (NFPOs).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] While an NFPO does not profit its owners, and money goes into running the organization, it is not required to operate for the public good.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] An example is a club whose purpose is its members' enjoyment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Other examples of NFPOs include credit unions, sports clubs, and advocacy groups.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations provide services to the community such as aid and development programs, medical research, education, and health services.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some nonprofits are both member-serving and community-serving.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Examples of these are homeowners associations, the American Red Cross, and Habitat for Humanity.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In 2020, some nonprofit organizations began using microblogging (brief videos with short text formats) on TikTok to reach Gen Z, engage with community stakeholders, and overall build community.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] TikTok allowed for innovative engagement between nonprofit organizations and younger generations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some organizations offer new, positive-sounding alternative terminology to describe the sector.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The term *civil society organization* (CSO) has been used by a growing number of organizations, including the *Center for the Study of Global Governance*.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The term *citizen sector organization* (CSO) has also been advocated to describe the sector – as one of citizens, for citizens – by organizations including Ashoka: Innovators for the Public.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Advocates argue that these terms describe the sector in its own terms, without relying on terminology used for the government or business sectors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] However, use of terminology by a nonprofit of self-descriptive language that is not legally compliant risks confusing the public about nonprofit abilities, capabilities, and limitations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In some countries nonprofits may apply for tax-exempt status.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Tax exemptions have been justified by community benefit of some organizations.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Studies argue that the community benefits of non-profits have be overestimated and can be negative compared to for-profit organizations when including the cost of the tax exemptions and costs due to financial mismanagement.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The discretionary process of tax exemptions application can result in corruption or fraud.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, to be exempt from federal income taxes, the organization must meet the requirements set forth in the Internal Revenue Code (IRC).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Granting nonprofit status is done by the state, while granting tax-exempt designation (such as IRC 501(c)) is granted by the federal government via the IRS.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] This means that not all nonprofits are eligible to be tax-exempt.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] For example, employees of non-profit organizations pay taxes from their salaries, which they receive according to the laws of the country.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] NPOs use the model of a double bottom line in that furthering their cause is more important than making a profit, though both are needed to ensure the organization's sustainability.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] An advantage of nonprofits registered in the UK is that they benefit from some reliefs and exemptions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Charities and nonprofits are exempt from Corporation Tax as well as the trustees being exempt from Income Tax.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] There may also be tax relief available for charitable giving, via Gift Aid, monetary donations, and legacies.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Financial mismanagement is a particular problem with NPOs because the employees are not accountable to anyone who has a direct stake in the organization.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] For example, an employee may start a new program without disclosing its complete liabilities.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The employee may be rewarded for improving the NPO's reputation, making other employees happy, and attracting new donors.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Liabilities promised on the full faith and credit of the organization but not recorded anywhere constitute accounting fraud.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] But even indirect liabilities negatively affect the financial sustainability of the NPO, and the NPO will have financial problems unless strict controls are instated.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some commenters have argued that the receipt of significant funding from large for-profit corporations can ultimately alter the NPO's functions.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] A frequent measure of an NPO's efficiency is its expense ratio (i.e. expenditures on things other than its programs, divided by its total expenditures).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Tax exempt status of NPOs can, under circumstances such as mismanagement, create negative value for society.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Reduced transparency requirements or limitations on freedom of information laws can in some cases result in financial crimes, see also non-profit organizations and access to public information.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Low wages have resulted in some cases in exploitation of labour.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] While many established NPOs are well-funded and comparative to their competitors, many more are independent and must be creative with which incentives they use to attract and maintain people.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] The initial interest for many is the remuneration package, though many who have been questioned after leaving an NPO have reported that it was stressful work environments and the workload.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Public- and private-sector employment have, for the most part, been able to offer more to their employees than most nonprofit agencies throughout history.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Either in the form of higher wages, more comprehensive benefit packages, or less tedious work, the public and private sectors have enjoyed an advantage over NPOs in attracting employees.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Traditionally, the NPO has attracted mission-driven individuals who want to assist their chosen cause.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Compounding the issue is that some NPOs do not operate in a manner similar to most businesses, or they operate only on a seasonal basis.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] This leads many young and driven employees to forego NPOs in favor of more stable employment.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Today, however, nonprofit organizations are adopting methods used by their competitors and finding new means to retain their employees and attract the best of the newly minted workforce.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Some believe that most nonprofits will never be able to match the pay of the private sector. and therefore should focus their attention on implementing pleasurable work environments.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] For some, a good environment is more important than salary.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Other incentives that could be implemented are flexible work hours.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Founder's syndrome is an issue some organizations experience as they expand.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/nonprofit-organization] Dynamic founders, who have a strong vision of how to operate the project, try to retain control of the organization, even as new employees or volunteers want to expand the project's scope or change policy.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The **Society for Historical Archaeology** (SHA) is a professional organization of scholars concerned with the archaeology of the modern world (15th century-present).
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] Founded in 1967, the SHA promotes scholarly research and the dissemination of knowledge pertaining to historical archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The society is specifically interested in the identification, excavation, interpretation, and conservation of sites and materials on land and underwater.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] It is the largest such organization in the world and the third-largest anthropological organization in the United States.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The society may additionally concern itself with European, Oceanic, African, and Asian archaeology having definite bearing upon scholarly problems in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The SHA’s “Ethical Principles of The Society for Historical Archaeology” provide further guidance to society members, historical archaeologists, and those in allied fields regarding one’s ethical obligations to the archaeological record, colleagues, employers, and the public.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] With the National Historic Preservation Act of 1966 and the United States’ approaching Bicentennial, the mid-twentieth century witnessed a renewed interest in colonial America and a growing scholarly interest in the archaeology of the modern world.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] These trends encouraged the development of a professional organization devoted to the study and practice of historical archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] At the 1958 Annual Meeting of the American Anthropological Association in Washington, D.C., John L.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] Cotter chaired a symposium on the Role of Archaeology in Historical Research.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] Jelks, Edward Larrabee, and Stanley South subsequently discussed forming a society devoted to historical archaeology.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] Jelks, following a second such discussion at the meeting of the Central States Anthropological Society in St.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] Louis in 1966, began to plan an “International Conference on Historical Archaeology." That conference was held January 6–7, 1967, at Southern Methodist University in Dallas, Texas.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The conference drew 112 attendees, with 17 papers by scholars including Charles Cleland, James Deetz, Bernard Fontana, J.C.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] "Pinky" Harrington, and Roderick Sprague.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The SHA was officially incorporated on April 1, 1968, in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, and John Cotter was elected to serve as its first president.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] SHA publishes its peer-reviewed journal *Historical Archaeology* quarterly with online publication of Book Reviews and Technical Briefs.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The SHA reader series, *Perspectives from Historical Archaeology*, offers subject matter and regional selections of articles published in *Historical Archaeology*.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The SHA Newsletter is published quarterly in March, June, October, and December.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The SHA also maintains a blog where members and non-members read, share, and discuss topics posted by SHA leadership.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] After the 1967 conference in Dallas, the Society’s first annual meeting took place in 1968 in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The table below shows the meeting locations and dates since 2007.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/society-for-historical-archaeology] The Society, in association with the Advisory Council on Underwater Archaeology, also organises the annual Conference on Historical and Underwater Archaeology, which takes place every January for the delivery of papers and symposia as well as social and professional interaction.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] The **Submerged Resources Center** is a unit within the United States National Park Service.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] The unit is based out of Lakewood, Colorado in the NPS Intermountain Region headquarters.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] In 1976, the Submerged Cultural Resources Unit (known as SCRU) was formed and staffed by underwater archeologists, photographers, and service divers to provide the expertise required by managers of national parks with submerged lands.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] Renamed the Submerged Resources Center in 1999 to include natural resources, the core mission of the program has remained the same: to inventory and evaluate submerged resources in the National Park System and to assist other agencies, nationally and internationally, with underwater resource issues.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] Projects the SRC have been involved in include work on USS Arizona, the shipwrecks of Isle Royale National Park, and mapping the shipwrecks of Dry Tortugas National Park, among others.
[src:advisory-council-on-underwater-archaeology/submerged-resources-center] Daniel Lenihan, former Chief of the SRC, describes the founding of the unit and many of its exploits in *Submerged: Adventures of America's Most Elite Underwater Archeology Team*.
